<p><span style="font-size: 12pt;">                                                         </span></p>
<p><span style="font-size: 12pt;"><strong>Course Description</strong></span></p>
<p><span style="font-size: 12pt;">The aim of the course is to provide students with the critical and analytical skills to evaluate, design, and write a policy paper. A policy paper is a scholarly work that analyzes a relevant policy issue and provides evidence-based, actionable recommendations. Emphasis is placed on the identification of policy problems, the use of methodological tools to analyze them, and the design and presentation of potential solutions. Class meetings feature presentations of policy papers that address the students' topics of interest, discussions of research strategies employed by policy analysts, and assignments that bolster written and oral communication. Students learn about all aspects of policy paper design, including the identification of relevant data sources, techniques for analysis, and the proper method of presenting policy paper findings. Examples of policy paper topics include migration and refugee policies, social and economic inequality issues, environmental and sustainability issues, gender equality and gender-based violence issues, cyberwarfare strategies, counterterrorism strategies, and issues of international security and nuclear proliferation. While this course is open to all students, candidates in the Master of Liberal Arts, government or international relations, who are interested in the capstone track should enroll in this course the semester before enrolling in <a href="https://www.extension.harvard.edu/academics/courses/policy-analysis-capstone/25115?_ga=2.22214649.353796653.1499797215-2415368185.1499435828">GOVT E-599</a>.<strong> </strong></span></p>
<p><span style="font-size: 12pt;"> </span></p>
<p><span style="font-size: 12pt;"><strong>Course website </strong><strong> </strong></span></p>
<p><span style="font-size: 12pt;">Here you can find all the readings listed in the course schedule, class assignments and announcements. Make sure to regularly check the website for updates.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-size: 12pt;"><em> </em></span></p>
<p><span style="font-size: 12pt;"><strong>Readings</strong></span></p>
<p><span style="font-size: 12pt;">We will be using the following texts available on reserve at Grossman Library:</span></p>
<ol>
<li><span style="font-size: 12pt;">Pollock, Philip H.. <em>The essentials of political analysis</em> (Fourth Edition). CQ Press, 2012.</span></li>
<li><span style="font-size: 12pt;">Bardach, Eugene and Erik M. Patashnik. <em>A practical guide for policy analysis<strong>: </strong>The Eightfold Path to More Effective Problem Solving</em> (Fifth Edition). CQ Press, 2016.</span></li>
<li><span style="font-size: 12pt;">Smith, Catherine F. <em>Writing public policy. A practical guide to communicating the policy-making process</em> (Fourth Edition). Oxford University Press, 2016.</span></li>
</ol>
<p><span style="font-size: 12pt;">All the other course readings are available on the course website, under "Modules"<strong>.</strong></span></p>
<p><span style="font-size: 12pt;"><strong> </strong><strong> </strong></span></p>
<p><span style="font-size: 12pt;"><strong>Course Policies</strong></span></p>
<p><span style="font-size: 12pt;"><em>Grading Requirements</em></span></p>
<p><span style="font-size: 12pt;"><em>UNDERGRADUATE STUDENTS</em></span></p>
<p><span style="font-size: 12pt;"><strong>20% Class attendance and participation</strong></span></p>
<p><span style="font-size: 12pt;"><strong>20% In-class presentations</strong></span></p>
<p><span style="font-size: 12pt;"><strong>20% In-class policy framing exercise, on 9/14/17</strong><strong> </strong></span></p>
<p><span style="font-size: 12pt;"><strong>20% Legislative history, due on 11/09/17</strong><strong> </strong></span></p>
<p><span style="font-size: 12pt;"><strong>20% In-class oral testimony, on 11/16/17 and 11/30/17</strong></span></p>
<p><span style="font-size: 12pt;"><strong> </strong></span></p>
<p><span style="font-size: 12pt;"><em>GRADUATE STUDENTS</em></span></p>
<p><span style="font-size: 12pt;"><strong>20% Class attendance and participation</strong></span></p>
<p><span style="font-size: 12pt;"><strong>20% In-class presentations</strong></span></p>
<p><span style="font-size: 12pt;"><strong>15% Policy op-ed, due on 9/14/17</strong><strong> </strong></span></p>
<p><span style="font-size: 12pt;"><strong>15% Legislative history, due on 11/09/17</strong><strong> </strong></span></p>
<p><span style="font-size: 12pt;"><strong>30% Policy report, due on 12/14/17</strong></span></p>
<p><span style="font-size: 12pt;"><em> </em></span></p>
<p><span style="font-size: 12pt;"><em>Participation, assignments and exercises</em></span></p>
<ul>
<li><span style="font-size: 12pt;"><em>Students are required to </em><em>attend </em><em>class regularly,</em> <em>actively participate </em><em>during</em> lectures and sections, and keep up with the class <em>readings and assignments</em>. Class participation offers an opportunity to take a stance in policy debates, a fruitful exchange of ideas with other students, and clarification of policy issues.</span></li>
<li><span style="font-size: 12pt;">Each week, students will give in-class presentations on the case studies listed in the course schedule. Students are required to read only the case studies they are presenting on; and are recommended to only skim through the other ones.</span></li>
<li><span style="font-size: 12pt;">The <em>problem framing exercise</em> – due by undergraduate students only – is an in-class group exercise. Students will split into groups and will identify, frame and present a policy problem of their choice to the class. Further details will be given in class.</span></li>
<li><span style="font-size: 12pt;">The <em>policy op-ed</em> – due by graduate students only – is a take-home assignment due on the course dropbox on September 14 at 5:30 PM. The assignment consists in a 1000/1200 words piece that: appropriately and thoroughly frames a relevant policy problem; and advances evidence-based opinions on how to solve it.</span></li>
<li><span style="font-size: 12pt;">The <em>legislative history</em> is a take-home assignment due on the course dropbox on November 9 at 5:30 PM. The assignment consists in a 1000/1200 words piece that summarizes the legislative history of a specific policy issue or law.</span></li>
<li><span style="font-size: 12pt;">The <em>in-class oral testimony</em><em> – due by undergraduate students only – is an in-class simulation of a witness testimony in a public hearing. Students will split into 4 groups and</em> will prepare and present brief statement on a policy issue of their choice. Further details will be given in class.</span></li>
<li><span style="font-size: 12pt;">The <em>policy report</em> – due by graduate students only – is a take-home assignment due on the course dropbox on December 14 at 5:30 PM. The assignment consists in a 4000/4200 words piece that analyzes a relevant policy issue and provides evidence-based and actionable recommendations to solve it.</span></li>
</ul>
<p><span style="font-size: 12pt;"><em> </em></span></p>
<p><span style="font-size: 12pt;"><em>Grading policies </em></span></p>
<p><span style="font-size: 12pt;">The grades assigned by the teaching staff are final. Grade changes are admitted only in case of a documented computational or clerical error. Students who fail to complete the course will be given a failing grade. No incomplete grades will be given as a final course grade. Please, make sure to review the grading policies set by Harvard Extension School, available here: <a href="https://www.extension.harvard.edu/resources-policies/exams-grades-transcripts/grades">https://www.extension.harvard.edu/resources-policies/exams-grades-transcripts/grades</a>.</span></p>
