<p><span style="font-size: 12pt;"><em> </em></span></p>
<p><span style="font-size: 12pt;"><em>Academic integrity</em></span></p>
<p><span style="font-size: 12pt;">There are many forms of academic dishonesty that include but are not limited to: plagiarism, cheating, fabrication, falsifying records or official documents, aiding others in perpetuating one of the above. You are responsible for understanding Harvard Extension School policies on academic integrity (<a href="http://www.extension.harvard.edu/resources-policies/student-conduct/academic-integrity">www.extension.harvard.edu/resources-policies/student-conduct/academic-integrity</a>) and how to use sources responsibly. Not knowing the rules, misunderstanding the rules, running out of time, submitting the wrong draft, or being overwhelmed with multiple demands are not acceptable excuses. There are no excuses for failure to uphold academic integrity, and any case of suspected academic dishonesty will be immediately reported to the Administrative Board. To support your learning about academic citation rules, please visit the Harvard Extension School Tips to Avoid Plagiarism (<a href="http://www.extension.harvard.edu/resources-policies/resources/tips-avoid-plagiarism">www.extension.harvard.edu/resources-policies/resources/tips-avoid-plagiarism</a>), where you'll find links to the Harvard Guide to Using Sources and two free online 15-minute tutorials to test your knowledge of academic citation policy. The tutorials are anonymous open-learning tools.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-size: 12pt;"> </span></p>
<p><span style="font-size: 12pt;"><em>Collaboration policy</em></span></p>
<p><span style="font-size: 12pt;">You are encouraged to share and discuss ideas with your peers in the classroom and in <em>group</em> assignments. However, collaboration is prohibited with regards to all <em>individual</em> exams and assignments in and outside of class. This means that you are not allowed to discuss the questions, answers or any other issue related to the course individual assignments, exams, exercises or any other individual written work. Please speak to the Professor if you ever have any doubts about collaboration policies.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-size: 12pt;"><em> </em></span></p>
<p><span style="font-size: 12pt;"><em>Accommodation for students with disabilities</em></span></p>
<p><span style="font-size: 12pt;">The Extension School is committed to providing an accessible academic community. The Accessibility Office offers a variety of accommodations and services to students with documented disabilities. Please visit <a href="http://www.extension.harvard.edu/resources-policies/resources/disability-services-accessibility">www.extension.harvard.edu/resources-policies/resources/disability-services-accessibility</a> for more information.</span></p>
