ning out of time, submitting the wrong draft, or being overwhelmed with multiple demands are not acceptable excuses. There are no excuses for failure to uphold academic integrity, and any case of suspected academic dishonesty will be immediately reported to the Administrative Board. To support your learning about academic citation rules, please visit the Harvard Extension School Tips to Avoid Plagiarism (\u003ca href=\"http://www.extension.harvard.edu/resources-policies/resources/tips-avoid-plagiarism\"\u003ewww.extension.harvard.edu/resources-policies/resources/tips-avoid-plagiarism\u003c/a\u003e), where you'll find links to the Harvard Guide to Using Sources and two free online 15-minute tutorials to test your knowledge of academic citation policy. The tutorials are anonymous open-learning tools.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-size: 12pt;\"\u003e \u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-size: 12pt;\"\u003e\u003cem\u003eCollaboration policy\u003c/em\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-size: 12pt;\"\u003eYou are encouraged to share and discuss ideas with your peers in the classroom and in \u003cem\u003egroup\u003c/em\u003e assignments. However, collaboration is prohibited with regards to all \u003cem\u003eindividual\u003c/em\u003e exams and assignments in and outside of class. This means that you are not allowed to discuss the questions, answers or any other issue related to the course individual assignments, exams, exercises or any other individual written work. Please speak to the Professor if you ever have any doubts about collaboration policies.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-size: 12pt;\"\u003e\u003cem\u003e \u003c/em\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-size: 12pt;\"\u003e\u003cem\u003eAccommodation for students with disabilities\u003c/em\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003